{{Infobox Coat of arms |name = Coat of arms of Copenhagen |image = Greater coat of arms of Copenhagen.svg |image_width = 220px |caption = |lesser = Coat of arms of Copenhagen.svg |lesser_width = 100px |lesser_caption = [[Escutcheon (heraldry)|Escutcheon]]-only |armiger = [[Copenhagen]] |year_adopted = 24 June 1661 |crest = |torse = |shield = |supporters = Two lions rampant Proper armed and langued Gules |compartment = Cannon, with additional war equipment |other_elements = |use = }} The '''coat of arms of Copenhagen''' was granted (under its current form) on 24 June 1661<ref>{{cite journal | author = Anders Thiset | year = 1894 | title = Om danske By- og Herredsvaaben | journal = Tidsskrift for Kunstindustri | pages = 71 | language = Danish }}</ref> by king [[Frederick III of Denmark]] in appraisal of [[Copenhagen]]'s citizen's efforts in repelling the [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[siege of Copenhagen|siege and attack]] in 1658–1659. An accompanying [[Royal charter|royal letter of privilege]] granted the citizens of Copenhagen the same rights to own fixed property as applied to the Danish [[nobility]].
The central feature of the full arms are three towers rising above water, a symbol also appearing in [[:Image:København segl 1296.jpg|the town's seal]] from 1296. The water element refers to the city's original name ''Havn'' meaning "Harbour" ({{lang-la|Hafnia}}). The left and right towers represent the [[Absalon's Castle|castle]] of [[Absalon]], while the central tower originally depicted a church building inside that castle.<ref name=Bartholdy>{{cite book |last1=Bartholdy |first1=Nils G. |editor1-first=Peter Wessel|editor1-last=Hansen |editor2-first=Leon|editor2-last=Jespersen |title=Stormen på København&mdash;den svenske belejring 1658&ndash;1660 |series=København. Kultur og Historie |volume=1 |year=2009 |publisher=Københavns Stadsarkiv |location=Denmark |language=Danish |isbn=978-87-89457-27-7|page=147|chapter=Københavns byvåben i lyset af begivenhederne 1658&ndash;1660}}</ref> By the 16th century, the central tower was no longer depicted as a church tower; instead it had a gateway with a [[portcullis]].<ref name=Bartholdy /> The version granted by Frederick III modified the previous symbol by adding a knight carrying a raised sword in front of the gateway. The central tower features an oval with the king's ''F3'' cypher above the city gate, both elements in [[gold]].
The greater [[coat of arms]] features three [[Helmet (heraldry)|helmets]], banners and a wide assortment of military equipment. An oversized golden crown is shown above, but not affixed to, the central helmet. Two [[lion (heraldry)|lions]] act as [[supporter (heraldry)|supporters]] of the central [[Escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheon]].
